m.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fulk","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulke","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Fulk I de Rycote was born about 1170, in Rycote, Oxfordshire, England, his father, Richard de Rycote, was 26 and his mother, Mrs. de Rycote, given and maiden names unknown, was 24. He married Matilda Visdelou in 1195, in Rycote, Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1233, at the age of 65."},"et":{"circa 1170–circa 1233":"umbes 1170–umbes 1233","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","1196–1233":"1196–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Surnud","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","circa 1233":"umbes 1233","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"umbes 1170","1196":"1196","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","circa 1168":"umbes 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"circa 1170–circa 1233":"noin 1170–noin 1233","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","1196–1233":"1196–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Kuollut","1148–Female":"1148–Kuollut","circa 1233":"noin 1233","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"noin 1170","1196":"1196","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","circa 1168":"noin 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"circa 1170–circa 1233":"environ 1170–environ 1233","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1174–Female":"1174–Décédée","1196–1233":"1196–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Décédé","1148–Female":"1148–Décédée","circa 1233":"environ 1233","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"environ 1170","1196":"1196","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","circa 1168":"environ 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir Fulk I de Rycote est né environ 1170, à Rycote, Oxfordshire, Angleterre, son père, Richard de Rycote, avait 26 ans et sa mère, Mrs. de Rycote, given 